      textEn: [
        "In the spring of the fourth year of Qingli, Teng Zijing was demoted to be governor of Baling Prefecture. The following year, governance was smooth and the people content; all neglected works were revived. He rebuilt Yueyang Tower, expanding upon its former scale, and inscribed poems by Tang worthies and modern men upon it, entrusting me to write a record.",
        "I observe the grandeur of Baling: it lies in the single lake of Dongting. Embracing distant mountains, swallowing the Yangtze, vast and boundless, from morning radiance to evening shadows, its appearance changes ten thousand fold. This is the grand spectacle of Yueyang Tower, fully described by predecessors. Yet, connected to Wu Gorge in the north and reaching Xiao and Xiang in the south, exiled officials and poets often gather here. Are their feelings upon viewing the scenery not different?",
        "When continuous rain falls for months without clearing, gloomy winds howl, turbid waves surge skyward, sun and stars hide their light, mountains vanish from sight, merchants cease traveling, masts topple and oars break, and at dusk all is dark with tigers roaring and apes crying \u2014 ascending this tower, one feels the sorrow of leaving one\u2019s country, homesickness, fear of slander, a scene of desolation, and extreme sadness.",
        "When spring is warm and the sun bright, waves are calm, sky and water merge in boundless azure, gulls soar and rest, colorful fish swim, shore herbs and islet orchids flourish. When the long mists clear, the bright moon shines a thousand li, floating light dances like gold, the still moon sinks like jade in the water, fishermen\u2019s songs answer each other \u2014 what endless joy! Ascending this tower, one\u2019s heart opens and spirit soars, honor and disgrace are both forgotten, raising wine to the wind, what overflowing happiness!",
        "Alas! I have sought the hearts of ancient virtuous men, who perhaps differed from both these. Why? They were not elated by things nor saddened by themselves. In high office they worried for the people; in remote exile they worried for their sovereign. Thus in advancement they worried, and in retreat they worried. When then were they happy? They would surely say: \u2018Worry before the world worries; rejoice after the world rejoices.\u2019 Ah! Without such people, with whom shall I stand? Written on the fifteenth day of the ninth month of the sixth year."
      ],
